author: Leeanna Ellis
title: Karr scores 5 touchdowns as Eagles down Falcons
text:
Arlington's Zach O'Flaherty runs for additional yardage in the second half against DC West on Friday. Karr scores 5 touchdowns as Eagles down Falcons By Leeanna Ellis Buy Now Leeanna Ellis 
Arlington's Garris Karr fights for more yardage against DC West on Friday. Karr scored 5 touchdowns and ran for 158 yards on 17 carries in the first half. Buy Now Leeanna Ellis 
Arlington's Jake Vogt hauls in a pass from Andy Theiler to score in the second quarter against DC West on Friday. Leeanna Ellis 
Arlington's Zach O'Flaherty runs for additional yardage in the second half against DC West on Friday. 
VALLEY -- Garris Karr and the Arlington Eagles put on an offensive clinic Friday against DC West as the Eagles beat the Falcons 44-13. 
Karr, a junior running back, carried the ball 17 times for 158 yards and five touchdowns -- all in the first half. 
Arlington coach Steven Gubbels attributed the win to staying the course. 
"Each week, I think we have a had a better practice than the last week," Gubbels said. "We're still focused on getting better, which has been the same theme we always talk about and it showed tonight." 
The Eagles defense held the Falcons to 3-and-out on its first series and Karr blocked a punt to give Arlington the ball on the 25-yard line. 
A few plays later, Karr scampered into the end zone for a 9-yard touchdown run to give the Eagles the early 6-0 lead. 
Karr added scoring runs of 38 and 1 yards in the first quarter. He added his fourth touchdown on a 5-yard run following an Eagle fumble recovery. Karr's fifth score with 7:01 remaining in the second quarter gave Arlington a 31-0 lead. 
The Eagles found their passing game worked against the Falcons as well. 
Quarterback Andy Theiler found sophomore Jake Vogt for a 20-yard touchdown pass with 4:24 left in the first half. 
Arlington's defense came up big with several fumble recoveries and interceptions, including one by Sam Plugge, who ran it back for a 41-yard touchdown to give the Eagles a 44-0 lead at halftime. 
The large lead early gave Arlington the opportunity to give some of the younger players some varsity time on the field. 
"It was a great opportunity, not only to get our younger guys in a varsity game, but also for our older guys on the sideline. We talked at halftime about how they were going to coach them up." 
Arlington will play at home next Friday against Fort Calhoun, an opponent Gubbels knows will be tough. 
"We're going to have to bring our 'A' game because I know they will," Gubbels said. "We'll just work hard this week and put it out on the field on Friday."
